### Writing Files in Rust

Rust provides several ways to write data to files, from simple convenience functions to buffered writing.

---

### Writing Methods

| Method | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| `fs::write(path, content)` | Write string or bytes (overwrites) |
| `File::create()` | Create or truncate file, returns File |
| `File::append()` | Open for appending |
| `write!()` / `writeln!()` | Formatted writing via File |
| `BufWriter` | Buffered writing for performance |

---

### Examples

```rust
use std::fs;
use std::io::Write;

// Simple write (overwrites existing)
fs::write("output.txt", "Hello, Rust!")?;

// Open for writing (create or truncate)
let mut file = File::create("output.txt")?;
file.write_all(b"Hello, world!")?;

// Formatted write
writeln!(file, "Number: {}", 42)?;
write!(file, "Pi: {:.2}", 3.14159)?;

// Appending
let mut file = fs::OpenOptions::new()
    .append(true)
    .open("log.txt")?;
writeln!(file, "Log entry")?;

// Buffered writing (better for many writes)
let file = File::create("large_output.txt")?;
let mut writer = BufWriter::new(file);
for i in 0..1000 {
    writeln!(writer, "Line {}", i)?;
}
```

> **Key Point:** For simple writes, `fs::write` is the easiest. For multiple writes, use `BufWriter` for performance. Use `OpenOptions` for fine-grained control over file open behavior (append, read-write, create, truncate).

codeExample:
use std::fs::{self, File, OpenOptions};
use std::io::Write;

fn main() -> std::io::Result<()> {
    // Overwrite file
    fs::write("hello.txt", b"Hello, Rust!")?;

    // Append to file
    let mut log = OpenOptions::new()
        .create(true)
        .append(true)
        .open("log.txt")?;
    writeln!(log, "Program started")?;
    writeln!(log, "Operation completed")?;

    println!("Files written successfully");
    Ok(())
}
